      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right that my previous solution was incorrect. To calculate the sum of divisors, we can use the fact that the sum of divisors of a number i is equal to the sum of divisors of i-1, i-2, ..., 1, plus i. Here's the corrected version:\n\n```python\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    def sum_of_divisors(i):\n        if i == 1:\n            return 1\n        return sum_of_divisors(i-1) + i\n\n    return sum(sum_of_divisors(i) for i in range(1, n + 1))\n```\n\nHowever, this solution still has a time complexity of O(n^2) due to the recursive function calls. We can optimize it further by using dynamic programming to store the sum of divisors of each number as we calculate it. Here's the optimized version:\n\n```python\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    dp = [0] * (n + 1)\n    dp[1] = 1\n    for i in range(2, n + 1):\n        for j in range(1, i):\n            if i % j == 0:\n                dp[i] += dp[j]",
